snippet.textDisplay:
e-Niro is surprisingly (to me) an excellent car for the money. Its really underrated. It could do as the main car for almost anyone not requiring a tow bar. Incredibly good range under any condition, compared to any other EV, and it is more spacious than it looks like.

BTW, you would have gotten the bluetooth on the Model 3 working again by doing a MCU reboot (hold in both scroll wheels on the steering wheel). Its not like the other cars, that reboots the screen at every start, that is why it had a noticeable drain, and also needs a manual reboot from time to time.

snippet.textDisplay: Is this a good case for keeping to diesels? I recently drove my 2011 Mazda 6 2.2 diesel Sport, 652 miles in one day as part of a 15 day trip covering just over 3000 miles from Spain to England and back. The car has just gone above 100,000 miles. I averaged 50 plus mpg driving within the speed limits. The vehicle cost me 7,600 pounds, purchased from a Mazda main dealer four years ago. Apart from routine servicing and a set of tyres, the only other issue to date was the replacement of both ball joints. Everything works perfectly and the car still drives as well as it did when I picked it up on 55,000 miles.  Someone should carry out a review of this car.  Does anyone remember how we were talked into buying diesels back in the early nineties, by our government?

snippet.textDisplay:
This is the sort of testing that we need to see more of.

I’ve owned two Nissan Leafs for more than five years now, and am very used to the limitations & advantages - my favourite advantage is that I have done 100% of my charging for free for four years/80,000 miles.

You do get used to running the vehicle within its limits, and as long as you follow the ABC rule (Always Be Charging) you won’t be let down.

But I still use an internal combustion car for long journeys. EVs make wonderful second cars and town cars, but only a Tesla can rival their convenience when you’re travelling more than 150 miles in a day.

snippet.textDisplay:
The Tesla Model 3 uses 4.5% of its full pack capacity as the reserve buffer below 0% displayed charge. It reached 0% at 261.5 miles @ 252 Wh/Mile or 65.9 kWh. At full depletion it went 269.7 miles @ 257 Wh/mile or 69.31 kWh. That shows the 4.5% buffer as 3.41 kWh on this vehicle at the time of the test, which would equate to a full pack capacity at 100% SoC of 75.37 kWh. If tested from a fresh 100% SoC @ 257 Wh/mile it would have achieved 295 miles.

This equates to 85% of the UK rated range of 348 miles or 95% of the EPA rated range of 310 miles. Not debating anything, just liked doing some math based on data that I know. Excellent test, loved it all. Cheers!
